âœª What are Kubernetes Secrets?
1ï¸âƒ£ Kubernetes Secret is an object that contains a small amount of sensitive data such as login usernames, passwords, tokens, and keys.
2ï¸âƒ£ The primary purpose of Secrets is to reduce the risk of exposing sensitive data while deploying applications on Kubernetes.
#KubernetesSecurity

âœª Key Points about Kubernetes Secrets:
1ï¸âƒ£ Secrets are created outside of Pods, necessitating the creation of a Secret before any Pod can use it. ğŸ”’
2ï¸âƒ£ When a Secret is created, it is stored inside the Kubernetes data store, specifically in an etcd database on the Kubernetes Control Plane. ğŸ—„ï¸
3ï¸âƒ£ During the creation of a Secret, the data and/or stringData fields are specified, with the values for all the data field keys being base64-encoded strings. However, arbitrary strings can be specified for the stringData field if base64 encoding is not desired. ğŸ“
4ï¸âƒ£ The size of each Secret is limited to 1MB to discourage the creation of excessively large secrets to prevent memory exhaustion in kube-apiserver and kubelet. ğŸ“
5ï¸âƒ£ The immutable property can be set to true when creating a Secret, making them immutable and protecting them from accidental or unwanted updates that could cause application outages. ğŸ›¡ï¸
6ï¸âƒ£ After creating a Secret, it can be injected into a Pod either by mounting it as data volumes, exposing it as environment variables, or as imagePullSecrets. ğŸš€
#KubernetesDeployment

âœª Types of Kubernetes Secrets:
1ï¸âƒ£ Opaque Secrets: Default Secret type used to store arbitrary user-defined data. ğŸŒ‘
2ï¸âƒ£ Service Account Token Secrets: Used to store a token credential that identifies a service account. The https://lnkd.in/gr4Z9pcq annotation must be set to an existing service account name. ğŸ¤–
3ï¸âƒ£ Docker Config Secrets: Store credentials for accessing a container image registry using kubernetes.io/dockercfg or https://lnkd.in/gvnSV6tz values. ğŸ³
4ï¸âƒ£ Basic Authentication Secrets: Store credentials required for basic authentication with keys such as username and password. ğŸ”‘
5ï¸âƒ£ SSH Authentication Secrets: Used for storing data utilized in SSH authentication, requiring a ssh-privatekey key-value pair in the data (or stringData) field. ğŸšª
6ï¸âƒ£ TLS Secrets: Store a certificate and its associated key used for TLS, requiring tls.key and tls.crt keys in the data (or stringData) field. ğŸ›¡ï¸
7ï¸âƒ£ Bootstrap Token Secrets: Store bootstrap token data during the node bootstrap process, named in the form bootstrap-token- in the kube-system namespace.
